Introduction

General Assistant 2 (formerly known as General AI Assistant) is a desktop application developed based on Python Embed. It can read the clipboard, summon toolbar menus, and then complete corresponding operations through specific scripts.

For regular users: The software continues its focus on text processing and chatbot functionality from its predecessor, with added features such as advanced parameter adjustment for models compatible with OpenAI interfaces and real-time streaming capabilities. Additionally, it includes traditional search functions that allow users to quickly hover over words and summon the system’s browser for search. This provides a ready-to-use experience for regular users.

For advanced users: The software introduces plugin functionality, providing a rich set of interfaces for secondary development.

Preset Plugin Use

Call OpenAI

This feature is built on the OpenAI API compatible format. Before using this function, it is strongly recommended that you first learn about the concepts related to the request parameters in the OpenAI API.

Set Model

Right-click on the tray icon to open the settings window:

To interact with the Model (AI) tag, you can perform actions such as adding, editing, and deleting them.

Please fill in the API URL, Model, and API Key. The API URL and Model are required fields. If you are using a public model, also fill in the API Key.
Note: If the API URL is an HTTPS protocol address that does not have SSL , it may be blocked by firewalls.

Then, the model configuration has been loaded into the software.

Edit Toolbar

Click the “Toolbar” button in the side panel of the “Settings” window to edit the translation function in the toolbar.

Replace the Model with the newly added model.

You can also create a new tool:

Create a new tool named “Check Syntax Errors”.

Functionality Invocation

Now, let’s invoke the functionality we set up earlier:
Open an application with a text box (e.g., Notepad), and select the content you want to send to AI.
Note: The selected content will be sent as “user”.
In two seconds, press and hold Ctrl+C twice (make sure you lift both keys between each press). This will trigger the custom menu you created earlier.

Click Translate to English, select the content will be replaced with the translated sentence. (The accuracy depends on the model’s fluency rate)

You can also set up the model in advanced settings by clicking on “Plugins” from the side bar in the “Settings” window, and then click “Call OpenAI” to enter the configuration page for this feature.

Here, you can adjust the request parameters for each call to OpenAI.

You can hover over “❔” to view the role of each request parameter. Therefore, this help document will not elaborate on each one individually.
Notably, although the “Stream” feature allows you to see the tokens returned by AI in real-time, it is not a panacea. If you want to use the “callOpenAI” tool in applications like Excel, turn off “Stream” as it prevents bulk processing of table content.

chatBot

This feature is a chat window that can load an AI model and have a conversation with it.
The “set up model” steps are the same as “call OpenAI”, you can refer to execute.
Assuming you have configured your model, in the “settings/toolbar”, edit function

Edit Toolbar

Ensure that the plugin you are currently using is chatBot.py and modify the model to the one you have configured.

Click to save.

Functionality Invocation

You can find it in the menu where you double-click Ctrl+C.

You can also find it by clicking on the “Show Toolbar” in the tray when you right click the icon.

When you start the Chat Bot window, it automatically fills the chat input box with the contents of the clipboard.

You can further edit the content you need to input. Press 'Enter to send directly, press Ctrl+Enter to wrap.
For example, if you need to ask AI:

Write a short story about a robot learning to paint.

Click Send and AI will start thinking.

AI will provide corresponding answers.

Click the button to clear the generated content.

traditionalSearch

This function is a traditional search feature that allows you to quickly open the browser and perform a boxed traditional search by copying the clipboard content.

How to use

Press Ctrl+C twice in two seconds to summon the toolbar, then click on Traditional Search.

A browser will quickly open and search for the selected content.

Customizing Search Engines

To customize search engines, go to “Settings/Toolbar” within your browser. For example, if you want to change the default engine to Baidu, you would first open your browser and go to Google’s website. In the search bar, enter a custom keyword such as test.

Copy the text preceding test in the browser’s address bar.

Go to “Settings/Toolbar,” and edit the “Traditional Search” function.

Please paste the copied address into the Prompt field and click Save.

Close the Settings dialog and retry the function. The search engine has been changed from Bing to Google.

OpenAI Request Parameters (For Beginners)

This section will introduce the concept of request parameters, helping you better configure AI-related functions and enabling the AI to follow your instructions more effectively.

The AI API, which is the interface for exchanging information with the AI server, requires sending requests in a specific format to receive responses.

The API URL, or AI server address, necessitates specifying the model and API key when sending requests.

Let me know if you need further assistance!

Obtain API URL, Model, and API Key

Our models are categorized into paid and free models. When using paid models, your account balance will be deducted. Therefore, it is crucial to keep your API Key confidential to avoid financial losses. Although paid models typically offer better performance and lower hallucination rates (the probability of generating erroneous information), we strongly recommend using free models when you first start learning and using AI APIs to familiarize yourself with the mechanisms.

Currently, the models for which free API Keys can be easily obtained internationally are:

Google Gemini: https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/models/gemini
Cloudflare Workers AI: https://developers.cloudflare.com/workers-ai/configuration/open-ai-compatibility/
Cerebras: https://inference.cerebras.ai/

⚠️Notice:

  • Google Gemini and Cerebras are not available in certain regions. If you are unable to access them directly, consider using a VPN or proxy.
  • Due to compatibility issues between the interfaces of Google Gemini and Cloudflare Workers AI with Open AI, the current version of General Assistant 2 cannot directly invoke them. You can use One API to translate the APIs, enabling normal usage.
  • If you are located in China, you have more free options. You can visit Chinese Help Page to get other free API Keys.

Taking Cerebras as an example (assuming you can already access the console address mentioned earlier)
Register and log in:

Upon first entry, a modal window will appear, allowing you to directly copy the necessary information.

No worries if you accidentally closed it. You can find the available models and API keys here.

Thus, you have completed the import of API URL, Model, and API Key.

Roles and System Prompts: A Guide

In conversation AI, three roles typically emerge: System, User, and Large Model.

  • System: Directs the Large Model to adopt a specific role and perform a designated task. A commonly used system prompt with a high degree of freedom is: “You are an AI assistant, please respond to questions as required.”
  • User: Provides specific instructions to the AI based on the system’s guidelines, which can vary each time.
  • Large Model: Responds to the user by providing answers based on the system and user requirements.

You can learn how to build prompts on FlowGPT.

Advanced Development

Getting Started

General Assistant 2’s plugin module essentially serves as a python script runner. You can quickly open the plugins folder by clicking 📂 in Settings/Plugins and placing your Python scripts there.

All HTML files will be displayed on the plugin page. Clicking the plugin name allows access to its options in the Settings GUI. This feature is primarily for configuring plugin settings.

All Python scripts will be shown in the Tools modal window. You can select which of these scripts to call for this tool.

Example

Create a file named Helloworld.py in the Plugin folder with the following code:

from plyer import notification

def send_hello_world_notification():
	notification.notify(
		title="Hello",
		message="Hello World",
		app_name="General Assistant 2"
	)

if __name__ == "__main__":
	send_hello_world_notification()

Code analysis: Using the plyer module, a system notification is called with title Hello and content Hello World.

Create a tool and change the plugin to Helloworld.py. This tool does not call “prompts” or “Model”, so any value can be entered. Save the tool, bring up the toolbar, and select the Hello World tool.

The script ran successfully.

APIs

The following APIs can be accessed to enrich your secondary development capabilities:

1. GET Request APIs

1. /marked.min.js

  • Function: Obtain a Markdown parsing library.
  • Purpose: Render Markdown content within a frontend page.
  • Usage: Access the specified path to obtain the JavaScript file.

2. /getPluginFiles

  • Function: Retrieves a list of all .py files in the plugin directory.
  • Purpose: Dynamically loads available plugin modules.
  • Return Format: ["plugin1", "plugin2"]

3. /plugins

  • Function: Retrieves all .html files from the plugin directory.
  • Purpose: Loads the frontend interface of plugins before they are activated.
  • Return Format: ["plugin1", "plugin2"]

4. /plugin/<filename>

  • Function: Retrieves the specified plugin’s HTML file.
  • Example: /plugin/chatBot returns chatBot.html
  • Use Case: Loads a specific plugin’s interface.

5. /getConfig/<configname>

  • Function: Retrieves content from specified configuration files.
  • Supported Configuration Files:
  • toolbar.json: Toolbar settings
  • models.json: Model configurations
  • settings.json: Global settings
  • input.json: Input configurations
  • callOpenAI.json: OpenAI API parameters
  • Security Mechanism: Prevents directory traversal attacks.

6. /openPluginFolder

  • Function: Opens the plugin folder on the server.
  • Purpose: Provides quick access to the plugin directory for file management.

7. /locales/<lang>.json

  • Functionality: Retrieves multilingual translation files.
  • Supported Languages: en-US.json, zh-CN.json

2. POST

1. /savePluginConfig/<configname>

  • Function: Saves plugin-specific configuration.
  • Example: /savePluginConfig/chatBot.json
  • Request Body: Complete configuration data in JSON format.

2. /saveConfig/<configname>

  • Functionality: Generic configuration saving interface.
  • Supported Operations:
    • Add new configuration items (action: add)
    • Update existing items (action: update, requires specifying index)
  • Special Handling: Automatically updates the settings.json language setting field.

3. DELETE

Example: /deleteConfig/toolbar.json/1 deletes the second tool from toolbar.json.

Parameter Validation: Ensures the index range is valid.

⚠️Important Note

Port

All files in this interface will be at http://localhost:54900. Do not expose this port to public networks. Exposing this port could compromise your privacy (e.g., API keys).
